---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for International School Counselors | Compare Expat Plans";
const description = "Health insurance guide for School Counselors working internationally, covering school counseling abroad, student support services, and school counselor career mobility.";
const headline = "Insurance for International School Counselors";
const subheadline = "Coverage solutions for School Counselors practicing abroad, working in international schools, and building school counseling careers across global markets.";
const canonicalPath = "/guides/school-counselor-insurance";
const heroBackgroundImage = "/images/guides/school-counselor-insurance-hero.png";

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'coverage-needs', label: 'Coverage Needs' },
  { id: 'work-settings', label: 'Work Settings' },
  { id: 'credentials', label: 'Credentials' },
  { id: 'occupational-health', label: 'Occupational Health' },
  { id: 'work-demands', label: 'Work Demands' },
  { id: 'career-considerations', label: 'Career Considerations' },
  { id: 'faqs', label: 'FAQs' },
  { id: 'next-steps', label: 'Next Steps' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  canonicalPath={canonicalPath}
  heroBackgroundImage={heroBackgroundImage}
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

    <section id="overview">
      <h2>International School Counseling Careers</h2>
      <p>
        School counselors provide academic, social-emotional, and career guidance to students. They support student development, crisis intervention, and college/career planning. School counseling combines educational expertise with counseling skills to help students succeed.
      </p>
      <p>
        International school counseling careers are well-established in expatriate education. International schools worldwide employ counselors to support diverse student populations. Third culture kids, transitional students, and multicultural communities create unique counseling needs. Understanding different educational contexts and coverage requirements varies by location.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide addresses insurance considerations for School Counselors working abroad in international schools, American schools overseas, and diverse educational settings.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="coverage-needs">
      <h2>Coverage Needs for School Counselors</h2>

      <ComparisonTable
        columns={[
          { key: 'need', header: 'Coverage Need' },
          { key: 'why', header: 'Why It Matters' },
          { key: 'typical', header: 'Coverage Situation?' },
        ]}
        rows={[
          { need: 'Mental health support', why: 'Vicarious trauma, student crises', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'General health coverage', why: 'Professional health maintenance', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Preventive care', why: 'Maintaining practice capability', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Vision coverage', why: 'Reading and screen work', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Immunizations', why: 'Working with children', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Emergency care', why: 'Crisis response availability', typical: 'Usually covered' },
        ]}
      />

      <h3>Emotional Demands</h3>
      <p>
        School counselors support students through crises, mental health challenges, and difficult life circumstances. Working with struggling students is emotionally demanding. Crisis intervention and suicide prevention work creates stress. Coverage should prioritize mental health support.
      </p>
      <p>
        International school counselors face additional challenges supporting transitional students. Third culture kid issues and family mobility create unique concerns. Self-care and professional support help manage demands.
      </p>

      <h3>Employment Structure</h3>
      <p>
        Most international school counselors are employed by schools with benefits. Employment packages typically include health coverage. Contract terms and benefits vary by school. Understanding your specific employment package is important.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-settings">
      <h2>Coverage by Work Setting</h2>

      <h3>International Schools</h3>
      <p>
        IB, American, and British curriculum schools employ counselors. Comprehensive benefits packages typically included. Working with diverse student populations. International schools offer structured employment.
      </p>

      <h3>American Schools Overseas</h3>
      <p>
        Department of Defense schools and private American schools abroad. Strong benefits packages. American curriculum and standards. American schools provide familiar professional context.
      </p>

      <h3>Embassy Schools</h3>
      <p>
        Schools serving diplomatic community children. Government-affiliated employment. Working with highly mobile families. Embassy schools offer stability.
      </p>

      <h3>Local Private Schools</h3>
      <p>
        Private schools seeking international expertise. Benefits vary significantly. Working within local educational systems. Local schools offer cultural immersion.
      </p>

      <h3>Online International Schools</h3>
      <p>
        Virtual schools serving globally mobile students. Remote work with location flexibility. Benefits vary by school. Online work offers location independence.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for School Counselors"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for School Counselors working abroad in international schools and diverse educational settings."
      buttonText="Compare School Counselor Plans"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

    <section id="credentials">
      <h2>Credentials and Professional Recognition</h2>

      <h3>Professional Education</h3>
      <p>
        Master's degree in school counseling or related field typically required. State licensure or certification in home country. Counseling training with specialization in schools. Education establishes professional qualification.
      </p>

      <h3>School Counselor Credentials</h3>
      <p>
        State certification or licensure requirements vary. National Board Certification available. ASCA standards provide framework. Credentials demonstrate professional competence.
      </p>

      <h3>International Credentials</h3>
      <p>
        Home country credentials typically accepted by international schools. Additional training sometimes requested. Cultural competency increasingly valued. International experience enhances credentials.
      </p>

      <h3>Specialty Certifications</h3>
      <p>
        College counseling specialization valuable. Crisis intervention training. Grief and trauma certifications. Specialty credentials enhance services.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="occupational-health">
      <h2>Occupational Health Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Vicarious Trauma</h3>
      <p>
        Exposure to student trauma and crisis. Suicidal ideation assessment. Child abuse disclosures. Mental health coverage essential.
      </p>

      <h3>Crisis Response Stress</h3>
      <p>
        Managing student crises regularly. Emergency response responsibilities. On-call availability in some positions. Crisis work creates stress.
      </p>

      <h3>High Caseloads</h3>
      <p>
        Large numbers of students assigned. Balancing reactive and proactive work. Time pressures and competing demands. Workload affects wellbeing.
      </p>

      <h3>Administrative Pressure</h3>
      <p>
        Non-counseling duties sometimes assigned. Balancing counseling role with other expectations. Advocacy for appropriate role. Role clarity affects satisfaction.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-demands">
      <h2>Managing Work Demands</h2>

      <h3>Student Caseload</h3>
      <p>
        Managing assigned student populations. Individual and group counseling. Classroom guidance lessons. Caseload determines workload.
      </p>

      <h3>Crisis Response</h3>
      <p>
        Responding to student emergencies. Threat assessments and safety planning. Coordination with families and administration. Crisis work is unpredictable.
      </p>

      <h3>College Counseling</h3>
      <p>
        University application guidance for upper school. Transcript preparation and recommendations. Application deadline management. College work is seasonal and intensive.
      </p>

      <h3>Transition Support</h3>
      <p>
        Supporting students through school transitions. New student orientation. Departure counseling for mobile families. Transition work is ongoing.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="career-considerations">
      <h2>Career Considerations</h2>

      <h3>International Opportunities</h3>
      <p>
        Strong demand for school counselors internationally. International schools actively recruit. Diverse locations available worldwide. Coverage typically included in employment.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Paths</h3>
      <p>
        Counselor to department head progression. Director of student support services. Administration opportunities in some schools. Multiple directions within international education.
      </p>

      <h3>Recruitment Process</h3>
      <p>
        Recruitment fairs and online platforms. Direct school applications. Agency placement services. Recruitment process is established.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Longevity</h3>
      <p>
        International school counseling careers can continue long-term. Experience valued highly. Physical demands minimal. Long-term international careers common.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="faqs">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm a school counselor considering international work. What should I know?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            International schools actively seek qualified school counselors. Home country credentials typically accepted. Cultural competency valued. Coverage typically included in comprehensive employment packages. Research specific schools and benefits.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What benefits do international school counselors typically receive?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            International school packages typically include health insurance, housing allowance or provided housing, annual flights home, and professional development funding. Benefits vary significantly by school quality and location. Research specific school packages.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">The emotional demands of student crises are affecting me. What support exists?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Crisis response work is emotionally demanding. Mental health coverage should be prioritized. Clinical supervision valuable where available. Self-care practices and professional support help sustainability.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">How do I find international school counselor positions?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Recruitment fairs (Search Associates, ISS, etc.) are primary venues. Online job boards for international schools. Direct school applications. Networking in international education community. Start searching 1-2 years before desired start.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Will my school counselor credentials transfer internationally?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Home country credentials typically accepted by international schools. Master's degree expected. State licensure or certification valued. Additional certifications enhance candidacy. Experience with diverse populations helpful.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What about coverage for my family?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            International school packages typically include family health coverage. Spouse and dependent coverage common. Review specific school benefits for family provisions. Some schools offer dependent education benefits.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Start by understanding what international school employment packages typically include. Most international schools provide comprehensive health coverage. Research specific schools and their benefits. Connect with international school recruitment resources.
      </p>
      <p>
        School counseling in international settings offers rewarding work with diverse students. Your coverage should support this important profession—addressing the emotional demands of student support, enabling international mobility, and protecting your health for a sustained counseling career abroad.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Protect Your School Counseling Career"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for School Counselors working abroad in international schools and diverse educational settings."
      buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

  </article>
</PageShell>
